<h2 id="custom-prompt">Custom Prompt</h2>

<p>Bash Prompt Customization</p>

<p>Now if you want to add a little color to make the interface more friendly or just want to have fun for a while, you can define color variables in the bash profile, and then update the prompt with the colors of your choosing. You can also choose the information to display by using the special prompt variable characters. Some examples:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>\uÂ  Â  The username of the current user</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>\hÂ  Â  The hostname, up to the first</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>\w Â  The current working directory</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>\nÂ  Â  A new line</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>The Bash prompt configuration is stored in the PS1 variable, so in order to save its contents youâ€™ll need to overwrite its value in a new variable.</p>

